<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-245-330  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 245 330.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Communications News  March 1990 v27 n3 p47(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The hybrid approach: mixing satellite with land-basedsolutions.(to back-up systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kamal, Sherin S.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Using both satellite and terrestrial lines in a hybrid approach tosystem backup lets the user avoid outages by prioritizing trafficand redirecting the most vital traffic.andP;  The hybrid approach alsoallows cost-effective use of backup facilities during normaloperation.andP;  Host-center backup is the dominant hybrid strategy,but it lacks flexibility, being limited to VSAT(very-small-aperture terminal) and point-to-point networks.andP;  Anintelligent satellite network superimposed on existing terrestrialservices is a more flexible strategy, with satellite capacitypooled, allowing dynamic balancing of traffic carried among sitesby satellite.andP;  The satellite network can be used for low-prioritytraffic during normal operation of the network.andP;  This low-prioritytraffic is automatically pre-empted in case of link or nodefailure.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Back-Up SystemsSatellite Communications.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Integrated diversity architecture. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>